Here's the vulnerable function:




function submitTransactionWithSignatures(
    address destination,
    uint value,
    bytes data,
    uint nonce,
    uint8[] v,
    bytes32[] rs)
    external
    returns (bytes32 transactionHash)
{
    transactionHash = addTransaction(destination, value, data, nonce);
    confirmTransactionWithSignatures(transactionHash, v, rs);
}
Normally, multi-sig wallets require that one of the owners initiate the transaction submission process, even if the required confirmations are gathered off-chain, to ensure that there's at least one owner's explicit consent for that specific transaction. This function, however, bypasses any such requirement.

Moreover, the confirmTransactionWithSignatures function, which is called within submitTransactionWithSignatures, does use the signaturesFromOwners modifier to check the provided signatures, but it does not validate who is submitting these signatures. This is a critical oversight because it assumes that the signatures are collected and submitted in a secure way by one of the wallet owners, which might not be the case.




function confirmTransactionWithSignatures(
    bytes32 transactionHash,
    uint8[] v,
    bytes32[] rs)
    public
    signaturesFromOwners(transactionHash, v, rs)
{
    for (uint i=0; i<v.length; i++)
        addConfirmation(transactionHash, ecrecover(transactionHash, v[i], rs[i], rs[i + v.length]));
    executeTransaction(transactionHash);
}
